Cross Optimization

Freddy R. Drennan

November 25, 2017

Loading the necessary packages

library(tidyverse)
library(lpSolve)
library(formattable)

Motivation:

I have a few ideas which may be useful. In my time at DFM, I have worked on writing the optimization code for the magellan tool. This optimization isn’t a true optimization. Instead, we look at key performance indications (KPI) like clicks and conversions. Some, from what I understand are related to importance. So for example eCPA1 as KPI is more important to the advertiser than eCPA2. The algorithm looks at the performance of these indicators and takes into consideration how much budget is left to allocate. This remaining budget is simply weighted to the performance of the KPI and then a campaign manager determines how strong they want this shift to be by an aggression parameter. A low aggression level, say \(10\%\) would shift the budget around less than \(100\%\). This is all done on a campaign level, within a particular channel. So for example, KPI may exist for a campaign in Search. In Search, a campaign manager (CM) can shift a budget around. In Social, a CM can shift a budget around.

We have been discussing a new tool, MagellanOMNI, which will look at KPI within say Social and Display, and then having looked at the KPI for Social and Display, rank each and then allocate remaining budget in the same way discribed above. I have thought about different ways of allocating budgets between different channels and this is what I’ve come up with. Instead of looking at KPI, we look at historical revenue and cost. Revenue for the advertiser which is linked to historical advertiser campaigns and the cost associated attaining that revenue. Then, based on this we create a function to maximize directly related to advertiser revenue and cost, while adding constraints which help channel budgets adequately. This method is meant to be a ‘set and forget’, true optimization. This is because there is only one adequate solution based on the parameters.

This, at the start would be an alternative way of shifting advertiser level budgets.

Starting Data:

# Revenue variables

initial_data <- 
  tibble(
    origin  = c(
      'search', 
      'display', 
      'youtube', 
      'gmail'
    ),
    revenue = c(
      225776, 
      99292, 
      4120, 
      2472
    ) %>%  currency(),
    cost    = c(
      8827,
      5172,
      833,
      423
    ) %>% currency()
  ) %>% 
    mutate(
      roi = (revenue - cost) / cost %>% currency()
    )


initial_data

Variables and the Objective Function

Declaration of variables:

  • \(x_1\) = Search Ads Budget
  • \(x_2\) = Display Ads Budget
  • \(x_3\) = YouTube Ads Budget
  • \(x_4\) = Gmail Ads Budget

Objective Function (What we want to maximize):

The coefficients for the objective function are the ROI weights. So, for our case here, the objective function is:

\[ \text{max}\;(24.57\;x_1 \;+18.20\;x_2\;+3.95\;x_1\;+4.85\;x_1) \]

Because the coefficients are in terms of \(\frac{\text{revenue}}{\text{cost}}\), when we multiply each coefficient by \(x_1...x_n\), we are creating an expected revenue.

So for example, historically we got about 25 dollars in revenue for search for each dollar spent in advertisements. We might assume that a budget of 100 dollars (\(x_1\)) would theoretically get the advertiser approximately \(\$2457\) in revenue. With this in mind, if the approach was to simply maximize advertiser revenue we would stop here and put all money into search. The real world is not so forgiving.

If we wanted the maximum return from the stock market, we would put all our money into one penny stock and pray it blows up. So, in the case of stocks, maximum return isn’t the only factor. We have to consider the risk involved, the benefits of diversification, etc. Basically, there are constraints involved which make an algorithm useful based on human input.

This human input may look like the following:

  • Total budget for all digital ads will not exceed 15000
  • Minimum: 3000 should be spent on Display ads
  • Minimum: 400 should be spent on Social YouTube
  • Display Ads and YouTube ads must exceed 60% of total budget
  • YouTube Ads should not cost more than Gmail Ads.
  • Minimum 1500 fee, where margin in each channel may be considered a factor.

There are four different inputs required for this optimization.

  • A matrix of coefficients which determine a relationship for all the variables for each constraint. This is the matrix A.
  • A vector indicating the right hand side of the equations. A vector of outcomes for the different variables. This is b.
  • A direction vector indicating an inequality direction, dir.
  • A vector indicating the equation we wish to maximize, obj.
A <-  
  matrix(
    c(
     1,    1,    1,    1,
     0,    1,    0,    0,
     0,    0,    1,    0,
  -0.6,  0.4,  0.4, -0.6,
     0,    0,   -1,    1, 
   .13,  .09,  .02,  .03
    ),
  ncol = 4,
  byrow = TRUE
  )

b <- 
  c(
    15000,
    3000,
    400,
    0,
    0,
    1500
  )

dir <- 
c(
  "<=",
  ">=",
  ">=",
  ">=",
  ">=",
  ">="
)

# $24.58*x_1 + $18.20*x_2 + $3.95*x_3 + $4.84*x_4 
obj <- 
  c(
    initial_data$roi
  )
##                                            dir b    
## [1,] constraint one:   1    1    1    1    <=  15000
## [2,] constraint two:   0    1    0    0    >=  3000 
## [3,] constraint three: 0    0    1    0    >=  400  
## [4,] constraint four:  -0.6 0.4  0.4  -0.6 >=  0    
## [5,] constraint five:  0    0    -1   1    >=  0    
## [6,] constraint six:   0.13 0.09 0.02 0.03 >=  1500

So let’s talk about this now!

Constraint One:

The first constraint is that the maximum budget allocated to these four channels is at least $15,000 dollars. So, the first row can be written as follows:

\[ x_1 + x_2 + x_3 + x_4 \leq 15000 \]

Where \(x_1...x_n\) are the budgets allocated to each channel. We don’t have any numbers other than 1 in the row because the weight of each dollar is not important. A dollar equals a dollar.

Constraint Two:

When we add zeroes for \(x_1, x_3,\) and \(x_4\) we are removing them from that part of the optimization. In the case for constraint two, the equation is written:

\[ x_2 \geq 3000 \]

Here we specify that at least \(\$3000\) dollars are to be spent on Display ads. This is the first example where we can see how the objective function’s maximum potential will decrease. This is because the overall best channel is Search, but we’ve decided that it makes sense to allocate a little bit of money to Display ads.

Constraint Three:

When we add zeroes for \(x_1, x_2,\) and \(x_4\) we are removing them from that part of the optimization. In the case for constraint two, the equation is written:

\[ x_3 \geq 400 \]

This means that \(x_3\), or YouTube ads must be allocated at least \(400\) dollars to spend.

s = lp(
  "max", # Maximize or minimize function
  obj,   # Objective function to maximize
  A,     # constraint matrix
  dir,   # direction of equalities
  b      # b vector of constraint coeffs
)

solution <- 
  s$solution

names(solution) <- 
  initial_data %>% 
  pull(origin) %>% 
  paste0("Budget-", .)
A %*% solution %>% 
  round(2)
##       [,1]
## [1,] 15000
## [2,]  8600
## [3,]   400
## [4,]     0
## [5,]     0
## [6,]  1522

Cleaning up data to display

sol_tib <- 
  tibble(
  x_1 = rep(NA, 6),
  x_2 = rep(NA, 6),
  x_3 = rep(NA, 6),
  x_4 = rep(NA, 6)
)

for(i in 1:nrow(A)) {
  solz <- 
    paste0(A[i,], " * ", solution, " + ") %>% 
    noquote 
  
  sol_tib[i, 1:4] <- 
    solz
}

sol_tib <-
  sol_tib %>% 
  mutate(
    equals            = rep("=", 6),
    sol               = A%*%solution %>% round(2),
    x_4               = sub("\\+", "", x_4) %>% str_trim,
    'constraints==>'  = rep("...", 6),
    dir               = dir,
    b                 = b
  ) %>% 
  as.data.frame
